Clean energy will see growth irrespective of whether we slip into recession.‚ÄúThe IRA‚Äôs programs and incentives will keep flowing no matter the macro environment, which makes betting on clean energy one of the most certain economic trends of the next few years.‚Äù (The Atlantic)
The law is likely to stay regardless of political shifts. ‚ÄúRepublican-leaning states are likely to see the most investment, job, and economic benefits from the IRA‚Äù

IRA also addresses methane emissions that globally account for ~30% of global warming.‚ÄúThe Methane Emission Reduction Program charges oil, gas operators for wasteful emissions. The fee starts at $900/metric ton in 2024, giving companies big incentive to reduce methane pollution‚Äù

At the household level, The IRA provides up to $28,500 in incentives, albeit variable, for electrifying houses. Steps like installing heat pumps to replace their furnace and water heater, buying an EV, and utilizing rooftop solar merit these rewards. (American Progress)

IRA for businesses: There exists ~10-30% in tax credit for clean energy production, using American-made equipment, initiating projects in underserved/low-income communities including federally-subsidized affordable housing projects. Bonus credits for paying prevailing wages.
The tax credit incentives are largest for corporations comprising approximately 55% of total federal investments under the act.

Contesting CBO's estimate, Credit Suisse‚Äôs estimate lies at $800 billion. Partly because the government will reward 45q carbon credits to businesses that meet their eligibility criteria, regardless, and they don‚Äôt have a budget for uncapped carbon credits.

The law includes approximately $369 billion (CBO estimate) in incentives for clean energy and climate-related program spending, including funding to encourage carbon capture, utilization, and storage (CCUS) projects.(image source: Rhodium Group) https://t.co/to4QIMV4od

The IRA is a landmark US federal law aimed at reducing the budget deficit. The act seeks to curb inflation, increase domestic energy production and manufacturing, reduce energy production costs, and curb emissions‚Äìin the long-run.
